Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll use a tactical developing move. I notice that your knight on f3 is currently “shielding” your queen on d1 from the long diagonal coming from my bishop on g4. By moving my knight from f6 to e4, I not only step into a very central post but also set a tactical trap: if you ever let your knight on f3 move or capture on e4, the moment it vacates f3 the bishop on g4 will have a clear line to your queen on d1.

So I’ll play:

make_move f6e4

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play a checking move. Based on the board:

• Black’s queen is on e4, and by moving it diagonally to f3 (i.e. playing e4f3), we give check.
• After Qf3, the White king on f2 finds that all its adjacent squares are controlled except g1 (g1 is covered by neither Black’s queen nor bishop). In fact, a careful look shows:
  – f1 is attacked by the queen along file f.
  – e1 is covered by the bishop on c3 (since c3→d2→e1).
  – e2 and g2 fall on the queen’s rank/diagonals.
  – e3, f3, and g3 are also controlled.
Thus, White’s only reply is Kg1, driving the king toward the corner where Black’s pieces will soon coordinate a mate.

So I’ll now make the move:

make_move e4f3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play  make_move g3g4

Let me explain briefly my reasoning. In the current position Black’s queen sits on g3 and has several options. An immediate capture on g1 (Qxg1) would seemingly win the loose white knight—but it fatally drops the queen on the d4–e3–f2–g1 diagonal, allowing White’s bishop on d4 to recapture. Instead, I prefer to reposition the queen to g4. On g4 the queen remains active, avoids the dangerous diagonals of White’s bishops, and keeps options open for further pressure. 

Thus, I choose make_move g3g4.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one very strong candidate is to use the bishop on d5. Notice that from d5 the bishop sits on the same diagonal as the white rook on e4 and the white king on f3. By playing Bd5xe4 you capture the white rook while simultaneously giving check (since the bishop on e4 would then attack the white king on f3). The white king will be forced to recapture—exchanging your bishop for a rook. This trade is clearly favorable, as you win the exchange. 

Therefore, I'll answer with:

make_move d5e4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for a knight move. After careful inspection, I like the idea of improving my knight on a5. It currently sits on a5 and has several options. One particularly attractive move is to jump it to b3. From b3 the knight will attack two white pieces simultaneously—a fork: it will be eyeing the rook on a1 and the bishop on d2. Since the rook is worth considerably more than the knight on a3 (or any minor piece white might have in its place), this fork should force white into a difficult choice.

Thus, I’ll make the move:

make_move a5b3

Moving from a3 to b3 puts the white king on b6 in check along the b‐file (since b3, b4, …, b8 will be controlled by the rook) and it cannot capture our rook (it’s too far away)–yet it still must leave check even though it will have some escape squares. Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I’d like to use our queen to put the white king under pressure while keeping it safe from capture. (Recall that the white king sits on b2; we must avoid moving our queen too close where it could be captured.) One promising idea is to move the queen from d3 to d2. On d2 the queen gives check by attacking along the second rank (hitting b2) as well as along its file and diagonals (covering additional escape squares).

Here’s the reasoning for Qd2:
• From d2 the queen controls the entire second rank. This means white’s king at b2 must leave.
• The queen’s diagonals from d2 (for example NW: c3, b4, a5, and SW: c1) cut off some of the adjacent squares around b2.
• Importantly, d2 is not adjacent to b2, so the white king cannot simply capture our queen.

After 1…Qd2 check, the white king’s legal moves are limited (for example, white might try Ka1, Ka3, Kb1, or Kb3), and in each case our material advantage should lead to a forced mating net soon.

Thus, I will now make the move:

make_move d3d2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one promising candidate is to use the knight on f3. Notice that from f3 the knight can jump to d4. This move is very attractive for two reasons:

1. It’s a knight move that gives check. From d4 the knight attacks e2—where the white king sits—forcing white to immediately respond to the check.
2. At the same time the knight on d4 eyes the pawn on f5 (on rank 5, file f), which currently isn’t defended by any white piece. After white moves the king to escape the check, you can capture the pawn on f5 next, gaining material.

To explain further: 
• The knight on f3 moves in an L‐shape: two files to the left (from f to d) and one rank up (from rank 3 to rank 4). That lands it on d4.
• From d4 the knight immediately attacks e2 (since one of its possible moves from d4 is indeed to e2). That constitutes an immediate check.
• In addition, from d4 the knight can later hop to f5 (if the opportunity presents itself as white has to move to respond to the check), winning the pawn there.

Therefore, a strong move for Black is to play “f3d4.”

When you’re ready to commit to your move, respond with:

make_move f3d4

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

My reasoning is as follows: My queen, currently on d4, can safely travel along the NW diagonal to b6. Once on b6 it eyes the diagonal that includes the white pawn on a5—which appears undefended—and can later capture it. The queen’s placement on b6 keeps it active and central while avoiding any immediate tactical liabilities (for example, moving to d3 would be risky since the white king on e2 defends that square). 

So, I’ll now complete the move: make_move d4b6.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one forceful option is to bring our rook on c8 over to h8. In algebraic/uci notation that move is:

make_move c8h8

This move delivers an immediate check along the h‐file (with our rook on h8) against the white king on h2. After this check, the white king’s options will be very limited (it cannot stay on the h‑file because the rook covers it and one of the adjacent squares, g3, is controlled by our bishop on h4). This check should force the white king to step away (likely to g1 or g2), after which we plan to coordinate our two rooks (one already on h8 after our move and the other on a1) along with our bishop and pawns to quickly tighten the mating net.

So I will now play:

make_move c8h8

One active idea is to move our queen from e8 to h5. This diagonal move (from e8 to h5) is legal and puts White’s king on h7 in check (since from h5 the queen also controls the entire h‐file down to h7). With White forced to address the check, he cannot immediately capture our rook.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board you provided, I’ve analyzed the position. Here’s a brief summary of the key details (assuming the top row is rank 8 and the bottom row is rank 1):

• Black’s pieces are:
 – King on b8
 – Rook on f8
 – Queen on d3
 – Pawns on a6 (rank6, file a), on g7 (rank7, file g), and on b5, c5, f5 (all on rank5)
  
• White’s only piece is the king on a2.

One very attractive idea is to use the queen to deliver a checking move that cuts off all the white king’s escape squares. Consider the move:
  Qd3–b3

Here’s why Qb3 is so strong:
 1. It is a legal queen move along rank 3 (passing through c3, which is empty).
 2. From b3 the queen gives a check. With the white king on a2, let’s check its escape options:
  – The king’s adjacent squares are a1, a3, b1, b2, and b3.
  – With the queen on b3:
   • It controls the entire b–file (so b1 and b2 are covered).
   • It controls all of rank 3 (so a3 and b3 are covered).
   • It also directly covers a2 along the southwest diagonal (since b3 → a2 is one diagonal step).
 3. This leaves the only available move for White as Ka2–a1.

After that, Black can follow up (for example with Qb3–b2) to deliver mate. (For instance, from b2 the queen would cover the escape squares around the white king on a1.)

Thus, as Black the move
  make_move d3b3
is a very strong, forcing choice.

I will now play:

make_move d3b3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, Black’s pieces are very few—a king on c8 and pawns on a7, b7, f7, g7, and h7—while White has a king on b2, a rook on e7, and pawns on c3 and g3. One natural idea is to improve king safety. Note that the white rook on e7 controls squares on the 7th rank (to its left, d7 and c7) as well as along the e–file, so Black’s king must avoid stepping into those attacked squares.

Right now the Black king sits on c8. Its legal moves (ignoring checks) are to b8, d8, c7, and d7. However, the squares on rank 7 (c7 and d7) lie in the white rook’s path. That leaves b8 and d8 as safe options. Moving toward the center is often desirable in pawn endgames, so the move from c8 to d8 appears logical.

Therefore, as Black I will choose the move:

make_move c8d8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose to move my bishop from b3 to c2. This move restricts the white king’s mobility considerably – after the move, the white king on c3 finds that almost every adjacent square is either occupied or attacked (b2 by the pawn on a3, c2 is now occupied, d2 by the pawn on e3, b3 and d3 fall on the diagonal controlled by the bishop on c2, and b4 as well as d4 are covered by the pawn on c5). In fact, the white king will be forced to retreat to c4, further cramping his already limited options.

make_move b3c2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose to move my knight from e4 to c3. This move has a nice tactical point: it defends my d5 pawn indirectly. In fact, white’s queen on b3 is currently eyeing the pawn on d5 along the diagonal b3–c4–d5. By playing …Nc3 (that is, e4 to c3), I cover d5 with my knight. This means that if white tries to capture the pawn with 2.Qxd5, I will recapture immediately 2…Nxd5, winning the queen. 

So, my move is:

make_move e4c3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

After examining the board closely, I’ve discovered a very strong tactical opportunity. Note the white queen sitting on d3. Our dark‐squared bishop on f5 can access that square by the diagonal f5 → e4 → d3. Since d3 is occupied by the queen, the move Bxd3 (bishop from f5 captures on d3) is legal.

If we play Bxd3, white is virtually forced to recapture (likely with either the pawn from e2 or the bishop on f1). In either case we win a queen for our bishop—a huge material gain.

Therefore, I will execute the move:

make_move f5d3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

make_move e4f2

After careful thought I’ve decided to sacrifice the knight by capturing on f2 from e4. This move (1...Nxf2) forces White’s hand—if White doesn’t recapture, Black wins the rook on h1; and if White does recapture (most likely with the king), then Black can follow up with a forceful Qh4+ to expose the White king. This tactical idea leverages the fact that White’s kingside remains undeveloped (with the knight still on g1 blocking escapes) and the king is stuck in the center.

In fact, moving the queen from d8 to f6 (UCI: d8f6) not only checks the white king on f2 (via the open f‑file: f5, f4, f3 then f2) but also places our queen in an active central role. It forces White to respond immediately (likely by blocking with the bishop or moving the king), and given our huge material edge, this active check can help further destabilize White’s position.

So, I’ll go with:

make_move d8f6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1...Bf3+, moving my bishop from e2 to f3. This move delivers check along the diagonal f3–g2–h1. White’s king on h1 has no escape because:
• It cannot go to g1 since the queen on f2 covers that square.
• It cannot go to h2 as that square is also controlled by the queen on f2.
• It cannot go to g2 since the bishop on f3 controls that square.
There’s no way to capture or block the check, so this is checkmate.

make_move e2f3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1... N(e5)f3+.

This move, with the knight traveling from e5 to f3, delivers a check to White’s king while simultaneously attacking the rook on g1. White will have to respond immediately—most likely by capturing the knight with the pawn on g2 (g2xf3) to block the check (since moving the king would leave the rook en prise). In the ensuing complications, Black’s pieces will have the potential to exploit the weakened kingside and centralize the remaining knight.

(make_move e5f3)

♟ ♟ ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ♟ ⭘ ♟
⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♔ ♝ ⭘
⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position:

8 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ♜  ♚  ⭘ 
7 | ♟  ♟  ♟  ⭘  ⭘  ♟  ⭘  ♟ 
6 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ♔  ♝  ⭘ 
5 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘ 
4 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ♗  ⭘  ⭘ 
3 | ⭘  ♟  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘ 
2 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘ 
1 | ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘  ⭘ 
    A   B   C   D   E   F   G   H 

Black’s pieces are: 
• King on g8 
• Rook on f8 
• Bishop on g6 (which is safely defended by the pawn on h7, since a pawn on h7 can capture diagonally toward g6) 
• Pawns on a7, b7, c7, f7, h7, and b3

White has only a King on f6 and a Bishop on f4. With such a huge material advantage for Black, it is important to improve the activity of the remaining forces.

One natural idea is to activate the rook. Moving the rook from f8 to e8 (the move “f8e8” in UCI) centralizes it and prepares to cut off the white king’s escape routes while not neglecting the defense of the bishop on g6. (Note that the white king cannot capture the bishop on g6 because g6 is covered by the h7 pawn—recall that white king moving to g6 would be moving into a square attacked by that pawn.)

Thus, I’ll play:

make_move f8e8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play Qc1 to c4. This move checks White’s king along the 4th rank. In fact, after Qc1–c4 the only legal moves for White’s king are to a3 or a5, and then Black can mate immediately by moving the queen to b3 (if White goes to a3) or to b5 (if White goes to a5). 

So, my move is:
make_move c1c4

Based on the board, I see that our black pieces are positioned as follows (using standard algebraic notation with a8 at the top‐left and h1 at the bottom‐right):

• A pawn on a7
• A pawn on b7
• A pawn on h5 
• Our king on d4 
• The white king on b2

Since it’s our turn as Black and we want to make progress in this king‐and‐pawn endgame (by advancing one of our passed pawns), a strong plan is to rapidly push one of the pawns on the queenside. In this position both the a‑ and b‑pawn can benefit from a double‑step move. However, the pawn on b7 is particularly attractive because by advancing it with b7–b5 we further their progress while keeping the white king at bay.

Thus, I will advance the pawn from b7 to b5 with the UCI move:

make_move b7b5

I’ll now complete our turn with that move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position – with your pieces as Black (king on d3, queen on e6, and pawn on a7) and White’s lone king on c7 – a strong candidate is to use the queen to check the king and further restrict its movement. For instance, moving your queen from e6 to d6 (UCI notation: “e6d6”) delivers check. 

After 1...e6d6 the queen on d6 controls the d‐file, the 6th rank, and important diagonals (notably NW toward b8 via c7) so that White’s king on c7 can only escape to squares like b7 or c8. This check forces White’s king to retreat further, making it easier for you to coordinate your queen and king in the coming moves to deliver mate.

So my move is: make_move e6d6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for a central break. I’ll play:

make_move e7e5

Here’s my reasoning:

– Black’s knight on d5 is active, and while the tactical idea  …Nc3 (forking white’s queen and rook) looked tempting, it appears that white can safely recapture (for instance with Bxc3), so that tactic doesn’t win extra material.

– Instead, the move e7e5 challenges the center and opens up lines for our pieces. It’s a classical, active response that helps Black complete development and prepare for further central and kingside play.

Thus, my move is e7e5.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play  Qc2–c1 giving check. Notice that in the current position the white king on a1 is not in check—but it has no legal moves (a2, b1, and b2 are all covered by the queen on c2). Since a non‐checking move would stalemate White and yield a draw, Black must “break the stalemate” by checking the king. The move Qc2–c1 is ideal: after 1…Qc1+ White’s only reply is 2.Ka2 and Black will continue with a decisive attack.

So I now make the move: 
make_move c2c1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play  d3c2. 

This moves my queen from d3 to c2 along the diagonal, giving check to the white king on a2. Notice that from c2 the queen controls the entire second rank and its diagonals (for example, down left she covers b1 and indirectly restricts the king’s escape to b2 and b3), leaving white’s king with only a couple of safe squares (namely a1 and a3). It’s a very forcing move that limits white’s options and sets up a mating net.

Now it’s white’s turn.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll choose to move my queen from d5 to h1. This is a diagonal move (d5 → h1), and it puts the white king on c1 in check along the first rank. (In UCI notation, that move is written as “d5h1”.)

Before I commit, here’s a brief analysis:

• The white king on c1 has adjacent squares b1, b2, c2, d1, and d2. After Qh1, the queen on h1 controls all of rank 1 (so b1, c1, d1 are off‐limits) and some key diagonals (covering parts of the escape route). This forces the white king to choose from b2, c2, or d2.

• In contrast to other checks (for example, trying Qd2 would allow an immediate capture by the white king), Qh1 safely keeps the queen out of reach while restricting the white king’s mobility.

Thus, I’ll now complete my turn with the move:

make_move d5h1

This move delivers a check because from c2 the knight also attacks the white king on e1, and it additionally threatens White’s rook on a1. In effect, Nxc2 forks the king and the rook.

This tactical shot wins material by forcing White to respond to the check and then allowing Black to capture the unattended rook on a1.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board picture and after checking several candidate moves, I like the idea of activating the dark‐squared bishop. Notice that along its southeast diagonal from e7 the squares f6 and g5 are clear and finally h4 is occupied by a lone white pawn. Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, here’s a quick analysis of the position:

 • Black’s pieces:
  – King on e3
  – Pawns on a5, b5, c4, f2, g7, and h7

 • White’s only piece is the King on g2.

Notice that Black’s pawn on f2 is just one step away from promotion (since Black’s pawns advance “downwards” toward rank 1). However, if Black immediately plays f2–f1 with promotion, the resulting queen on f1 would be undefended. White’s king on g2 controls the square f1 (directly adjacent: f1–g2 differ by one file and one rank), and would be able to capture the promoted queen on the next move.

A better plan is to prepare the rook/queen promotion by bringing the Black king closer so that it helps defend the future queen. In particular, a move like King e3–e2 is very attractive. Once on e2, the Black king is adjacent to f1 (since e2 and f1 share a diagonal) and will defend that square. Then, when Black eventually plays f2–f1 (with promotion to queen, rook, or even knight if desired), the promoted piece will be protected; white’s king will not be able to capture it without illegally moving next to Black’s king.

Thus, my move as Black is:

make_move e3e2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, my pieces are as follows (with black pieces in their standard symbols):

• King on e2  
• Queen on f3  
• Pawns on a5, b5, c4, g7, and h7  

White’s only piece is the king on h4.

Aiming for a quick win, one idea is to deliver a forcing check so that the white king’s escape options are very limited. One promising candidate is moving the queen from f3 to h1. (In UCI notation this is “f3h1”.)

Let’s examine that move briefly:

After 1...f3h1, the queen lands on h1. From h1 the queen controls:
 – the entire h‐file (so h2, h3, h4, h5, etc.),
 – the first rank (horizontally), and
 – the up‐left diagonal (h1 → g2 → f3 → e4 …).

White’s king on h4 has at most these adjacent squares:
 • g3, g4, g5, h3, h5.

Because the queen on h1 covers the whole h‐file it takes away h3 and h5; and the vertical “g–file” control (if the king tries to run toward the queen’s direction) further restricts the escapes. (A careful look shows that after Qh1, the only legal king moves are g3, g4, and g5.)

Also note, the queen on h1 isn’t sitting right next to the white king. That means white cannot simply capture it. (There’s no other black piece defending h1, but that’s fine—since it’s safely out of reach of the white king.)

While this move doesn’t deliver mate immediately, it’s very forcing and restricts the white king’s options dramatically. In a king-and-queen versus lone king endgame, such checking moves are part of the winning technique.

Thus, I choose to play:

make_move f3h1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play  Bishop from c4 to e2. In UCI notation, that move is:

make_move c4e2

This move does not immediately deliver check, but it repositions our bishop so that if we later swing our d8–rook down to d1 (which would then deliver check along the first rank), the square d1 will be guarded. That way, white’s king won’t be able to capture the rook on d1 without moving into the bishop’s line of fire. It’s a preparatory move that helps tighten the noose around white’s exposed king while keeping our material advantage intact.

Your move!

⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play the bishop move from d4 to e5.

Before explaining further, here’s why this is a solid choice in the position:

Currently the white king on h1 has only one “legal” square available—but it isn’t in check (its three adjacent squares are covered: g1 is attacked by our bishop on d4 along the diagonal d4–e3–f2–g1, while g2 and h2 are guarded by our king on g3). If we “waste” a move that leaves that situation unchanged, white would have no legal moves on its turn and the game would end in stalemate. 

To avoid drawing and to keep winning chances alive, we must “give” white a move—that is, we want to remove one of the covering influences so that white’s king can move and avoid stalemate. Moving our bishop off the d4–e3–f2–g1 diagonal (while not giving any unwanted relief) does exactly that. The move  d4e5  places the bishop onto e5. From e5 its diagonals are:
 • SW: d4, c3, b2, a1
 • NE: f6, g7, h8
 • SE: f4, g3, h2 
 • NW: d6, c7, b8

Notice that with the bishop on e5 it no longer covers g1. That means white’s king on h1 will have g1 available as a legal move (since g2 and h2 remain controlled by our king on g3). By “unblocking” g1 we avoid an immediate stalemate and force white to move, preserving our winning advantage.

So I’ll now play:

make_move d4e5

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Move made, switching player

make_move a7a6
